Ans. Yes, the Faith that influences the Heart and Life, and stands in all times and trials, must be thus qualified. And the Faith, which is either dissembled, formal, wavering, unaffecting, careless, or irresolute, some one or other of which the Faith of all Sinners is, is like to have no such Blessed Fruits proceding from it: As Simon Magus's had not, whose heart was not right;
• or Agrippa's, whose Faith was but almost;
• or the Temporary Believers, whose faith • ell away because it wanted root. So that these different attendants, and various qualifications of Faith, make the difference in its Fruits and Effects, and distinguish the Faith of Saints from the Faith of Sinners.
